      <p class="mb-2">
        A few weeks before Christmas, one of the kids got the "Worst Case Scenario Survival Guide" for their birthday and proceeded to read aloud every page in the book during a long drive back from the lake.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-2">
        The chapter "How to Detect a Letter Bomb" was of particular interest to everyone so I thought "I know, I'll wrap a Christmas gift like a bomb and see if they were paying attention".
      </p>

      <p class="mb-2">
        As usual, I decided that this absolutely required a Rails app.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-2">
        I would create a bomb-like device and wire it to all their gifts. They would have to "defuse" it or their presents would be incinerated.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-2">
        The idea was to setup a touchscreen Raspberry Pi, create a game on it, and just attach some electrical wire from the apparatus to each gift.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-2">
        In order to sell this to the kids, I invented an evil elf named Malekith that is known for doing this kind of thing and had tormented my brothers and I when we were about their age.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-2">
        I sold it a little too well.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-2">
        I realized I needed to tone everything down a bit. I ditched the bomb apparatus and focused on a browser-based game and lightened up with the evil-elf-out-there-ruining-Christmas stuff.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-2">
        I also realized that teaching kids to try to defuse a bomb went against everything we had read in the book and, for anyone that hasn't read it, the official advice is "run away".
      </p>

      <p class="mb-2">
        Anyway, the family-friendly version of this idea became a successful game and I managed to save Christmas (by virtue of not ruining it).
      </p>
