  <section>
    <div class="font-bold text-3xl mb-2 text-gray-700">
      Game Play
    </div>

    <p class="mb-2">
      There are two versions of this game- the version specifically and personally made for my family (Story Mode) and a "public" version with more generic questions.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      The game's main menu features a normal "Start Game" button for anyone to play the public version and there is also a password field with a hint that only the kids would know and allow them to access their Story Mode.
    </p>    

    <p class="mb-2 font-semibold text-lg text-gray-700">
      Story Mode
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      After entering the password and entering Story Mode, the kids would be greeted by the mischievious elf Malekitch who explains the rules and stakes of the game.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      Essentially, Malekith has stolen all the Christmas presents and the kids would have to work together to answer a series of multiple choice questions (tailored to them) to reveal their location.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      If they were to get 3 questions wrong, Malekith would take off with all the gifts. Really though, they'd have just had to start over from the beginning.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      The kids would take turns answering 10 questions each. There is some game dialog in between players and one little "trick" where they are given the option to skip the game entirely and immediately reveal the location of the presents.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      This option (really the only path forward) instead starts a game clock and informs them they would only have 30 seconds to answer each question.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      I wanted them to feel a bit of pressure and excitement but not miss out on any of the questions due to a strict game clock so I set the JavaScript timeout to appear to be a 30 second countdown while really giving them 45.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      If the game clock were to expire, the players currently selected answer would be submitted for them. If there was nothing selected, it would automatically be marked wrong. Luckily, we didn't run into this in Story Mode.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      After successfully answering all 20 questions, there is a "final question" which is a riddle and the answer to the riddle was the actual location of their bags of gifts out in the backyard.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      The game went great, the kids didn't ever have to start over, and then we turned it over to the rest of the family to play the public mode.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2 font-semibold text-lg text-gray-700">
      Public Mode
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      As a bonus, and to allow anyone to play, I included the same game with generic Christmas questions and all the Malekith stuff and game dialog yanked out.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      The questions are basically regular Christmas trivia that you'd find if you Googled it. Reindeer names, Christmas movie questions, complete-that-Christmas-Carol, etc.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-2">
      The game is pretty straight forward- answer 10 questions correctly and you win. Answer 3 wrong and you lose.
    </p>
